solutions.content:
Micro explanation is this:

For a given string, s. of length N, we could split the string at any point from 1...N-1

Then we would have s1 and s2, which we could re-order to a string b which is either s1s2 or s2s1.

Let's try an example, for only 1 level of scrambling depth...:

s = hamburger
b = burgerham

We have some possible solutions:

1.)
h amburger
We compare with 
b|urgerham OR burgerha|m

2.)
ha mburger
We compare with 
bu|rgerham OR burgerh|am

3.)
ham burger
We compare with 
bur|gerham OR burger|ham

We see that #3 is a valid scramble since "ham" is a scramble of "ham" and "burger" is a scramble of "burger"

So, essentially we recursively check valid sub-scrambles, for being scrambles... 

Scrambles always have the same number of each letter. So this can be a quick heuristic to exit and side-search.













```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isScramble(string s1, string s2) {

        if (s1 == s2) { return true; }
        if (s1.size() != s2.size()) { return false; }

        string aComp1 = s1;
        string aComp2 = s2;

        int aLen = s1.size();

        sort(aComp1.begin(), aComp1.end());
        sort(aComp2.begin(), aComp2.end());
        if (aComp1 != aComp2) { return false; }

        for (int i=1;i<s1.size();i++) {

            string aComps11 = s1.substr(0, i);
            string aComps12 = s1.substr(i);

            string aComp1s21 = s2.substr(0, i);
            string aComp1s22 = s2.substr(i);

            string aComp2s21 = s2.substr(aLen - i);
            string aComp2s22 = s2.substr(0, aLen - i);

            if (isScramble(aComps11, aComp1s21) && isScramble(aComps12, aComp1s22)) {
                return true;
            }

            if (isScramble(aComps11, aComp2s21) && isScramble(aComps12, aComp2s22)) {
                return true;
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
};
```

