solutions.content:
Intiution: 
Step 1:
lets take a simpler example:  "abc" & "bac".  
Step 2:
abc can be split in the following => {a,bc} {ab, c}
on swapping the values you can also generate reverse of substrings {bc,a} and {c, ab}  

Step 3:
All possible combinations of abc from step-2 are {a,bc} {ab, c} & {bc,a} and {c, ab} 

Step 4:
Similarly "bac" becomes {b, ac} {ba, c} {ac, b} {c, ab}

Step 5: 
Take the Step3 and Step4 results and recursively analyze if any of the combination results in to same string, if it does its success. else its not. 







````
class Solution {
    Map<String, Boolean> memo = new HashMap<>();
    public boolean isScramble(String s1, String s2) {

        if(s1.equalsIgnoreCase(s2)) return true;

        String key = s1+"____"+s2;

        if(memo.containsKey(key))return memo.get(key);

        boolean answer = false;
        for(int i=1;i<s2.length();i++){

            String real_prefix = s1.substring(0, s1.length()-i); //(gr, e)
            String real_suffix = s1.substring(s1.length()-i);

            String real_prefix_no_echange = s1.substring(0, i); // (g, re)
            String real_suffix_no_echange = s1.substring(i);

            String prefix = s2.substring(0, i);   // (g, re)
            String suffix = s2.substring(i);

            boolean noExchange = isScramble(real_prefix, suffix) && isScramble(real_suffix, prefix);
            boolean exchange = isScramble(real_prefix_no_echange, prefix) && isScramble(real_suffix_no_echange, suffix);


            answer = answer || exchange || noExchange;
        }

        memo.put(key, answer);
        return answer;
    }
}
````

O(n^4)

